FOREWORD 
This is the first volume in a series of reports of excavations carried out in 2017 at what is referred to 
here  as  the  Wesley  Church  Complex.  This  complex  included  three  sites  that  are  included  on  the 
Victorian Heritage Inventory – H7822-1198 (118-122 Lonsdale Street), H7822-1199 (Wesley Church), 
and H7822-2349 (Jones Lane Archaeological Precinct). These three sites were excavated as part of the 
same  project  between  January  and  June  2017,  prior  to  the  construction  of  a  multi-storey  office 
complex that resulted in the complete removal of two of the sites (H7822-1198 and H7822-2349), and 
the disturbance of a small part of H7822-1199.' metadata={'source': '/home/unimelb.edu.au/hamzeie/Desktop/hv_hackathon/data/5187_118-122 Lonsdale Street H7822-1198_final report 21 Dec 2020.pdf'}

page_content='Artefact Summary 
Assemblage Size 
The artefacts are quantified by two fields: Minimum Number of Individuals (MNI) which tracks the 
minimum number of individual items present and Quantity (N) which is a count of the total number 
of  fragments  present.  The  total  number  of  artefacts  collected  is  1,169  fragments  (N)  comprising 
approximately 788 individual items (MNI). 

Catalogue 
The cataloguing methodology was to record in detail the excavated artefacts, using a comprehensive 
catalogue database designed by Dr Christine Williamson Heritage Consultants. This allowed the data 
to be searched and queried, which in turn aided the understanding of the artefacts and the activities 
that occurred at the site. Key information from this database was then transferred into the Heritage 
Victoria Catalogue Template, for consistency in the recording of sites across Victoria.' metadata={'source': '/home/unimelb.edu.au/hamzeie/Desktop/hv_hackathon/data/5187_118-122 Lonsdale Street H7822-1198_final report 21 Dec 2020.pdf'}

3. EXCAVATION METHODOLOGY AND AIMS 
The investigation of 118-122 Lonsdale Street H7822-1198 involved monitoring the demolition of the 
Princess  Mary  Club  building,  with  the  aim  of  exposing  any  preserved  19th  structural  remains  or 
deposits and determining the archaeological integrity of the area. The aim of the investigation was to 
obtain information relating to Melbourne’s early occupation and commercial development. This was 
to be followed by targeted excavations of any preserved 19th century remains (structural or material) 
relating to the buildings that had occupied the site prior to the construction of the Princess Mary Club 
building, with the intention of establishing the extent, nature and significance of those remains.' metadata={'source': '/home/unimelb.edu.au/hamzeie/Desktop/hv_hackathon/data/5187_118-122 Lonsdale Street H7822-1198_final report 21 Dec 2020.pdf'}
